 shape of the model means that the model can take any number of input examples, each of which is a vector of length 16, and will output a vector of length 32 for each input.</p><p id="8eb60895-b350-4655-ba3d-e4f22e098769" class="">The first dimension of <code><strong>(None, 32)</strong></code> corresponds to the batch size, which is the number of input examples that are processed at once during training or inference. Since the model can accept any number of input examples, the batch size is variable and is represented by <code><strong>None</strong></code>. During training or inference, you would typically specify a fixed batch size, but the model can handle different batch sizes.</p><p id="547f54a2-d994-4e52-b1d7-f9d4017641be" class="">The second dimension of <code><strong>(None, 32)</strong></code> corresponds to the output shape of the second <code><strong>Dense</strong></code> layer, which has 32 units. This means that the output of the model for each input example is a vector of length 32.</p><p id="002b1508-652c-41f1-b636-6ddb3629f672" class="">Overall, the <code><strong>(None, 32)</strong></code> output shape indicates that the model can accept input examples of variable batch size and will output a vector of length 32 for each input.</p></div></article></body></html>